---
import ProjectLayout from "../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro";
import PhotoGallery from "../../components/PhotoGallery.jsx";
---

<ProjectLayout
  title="OERC Research — Maritime Autonomy"
  subtitle="Ocean Engineering Research Center · Supervised by Dr. Wei Qiu · Jan – May 2026"
  logo="/logos/mun-engineering.png"
  logoAlt="MUN Engineering"
  logoClass="bg-white/10 p-1"
  context="Work"
  tags={["C++17", "Qt 6", "OpenGL", "GLSL", "NURBS", "IGES", "Arduino", "Raspberry Pi", "LiDAR", "PID Control", "KiCad", "OpenCV", "CMake"]}
>

  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="font-display text-lg font-600 text-white/80 mb-4">Overview</h2>
    <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed max-w-2xl">
      Three projects under Dr. Wei Qiu at Memorial's Ocean Engineering Research Center.
      I built a C++/OpenGL desktop app for hull geometry visualization and hydrodynamic analysis,
      wrote a research report on autonomous vessel communications for IMO/Transport Canada,
      and designed and built AEGIS, a scale-model autonomous SAR vessel, from scratch.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="font-display text-lg font-600 text-white/80 mb-6">Projects</h2>
    <div class="space-y-8">

      <!-- AEGIS -->
      <div class="glass-card p-6">
        <h3 class="font-display font-600 text-white/85 mb-1">AEGIS — Autonomous SAR Vessel</h3>
        <p class="text-xs font-mono text-white/25 mb-3">Arduino · Raspberry Pi Zero 2 W · LiDAR · MLX90640 · OpenCV · KiCad</p>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed mb-5">
          <p>
            AEGIS (Autonomous Environmental Guardian for Intelligent Search-and-Rescue) is a
            scale-model vessel targeting <span class="text-white/70">IMO Level 2/3 autonomy</span>.
            The problem it addresses is straightforward: Canada has the longest coastline in the world,
            Arctic conditions make crewed SAR patrols dangerous and expensive, and existing fleets
            can't cover it all. AEGIS is meant to fill that gap as a forward-deployed
            <span class="text-white/70">thermal search drone</span> that gets to the scene ahead
            of Coast Guard crews, scanning for people in the water and relaying conditions back to
            shore. The autonomy and comms architecture came out of
            my <a href="#mass-report" class="text-white/70 underline underline-offset-2 decoration-white/20 hover:decoration-white/40">MASS connectivity research</a>,
            which I did first specifically to figure out how a vessel like this should handle
            <span class="text-white/70">sensor fusion</span>, decision-making, and connectivity
            failover when satellite links drop.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Platform & propulsion</h4>
          <p>
            An <span class="text-white/70">Arduino Uno</span> drives the propulsion system through
            an L298N dual H-bridge controlling a brushed DC thruster motor and a rudder servo. Two
            VL53L0X <span class="text-white/70">LiDAR sensors</span> (forward and starboard) feed
            distance readings into a <span class="text-white/70">PID control loop</span> running
            at ~50 Hz for wall tracking and obstacle avoidance. Tuning the PID gains for the tank
            environment took most of the testing time since the hull's drag characteristics change
            a lot between dry-run bench tests and actual water.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Dual-processor architecture</h4>
          <p>
            The system splits across two processors over
            <span class="text-white/70">UART serial</span> at 115200 baud. The Uno handles all
            real-time motor PID and rudder control, because it needs deterministic loop timing
            and the Pi can't guarantee that. The
            <span class="text-white/70">Raspberry Pi Zero 2 W</span> runs the compute-heavy
            side: thermal imaging pipeline, camera-based obstacle detection through
            <span class="text-white/70">OpenCV</span>, GPS/IMU logging at 10 Hz, WiFi telemetry
            to the ground station, and <span class="text-white/70">3D thermal map compositing</span>.
            Commands flow Pi-to-Uno as simple ASCII packets (heading setpoints, speed targets),
            and the Uno sends back sensor telemetry and status flags.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Thermal scanning & detection</h4>
          <p>
            The SAR payload is an <span class="text-white/70">MLX90640 thermal array</span> (32×24)
            on a servo mount. It sweeps four positions using the sensor's 110° FOV to get full
            360° azimuth coverage. Each frame is tagged with GPS coordinates and IMU orientation,
            logged to SD card and optionally streamed to the ground station over WiFi. The frames
            composite into a <span class="text-white/70">3D thermal point cloud</span> of the
            vessel's surroundings. Human body heat (~30°C+) stands out clearly against open water
            at ~2-4°C, so the detection threshold is generous. When the system picks up a warm
            cluster, it locks the heading, triggers indicator LEDs and a piezo buzzer, and logs
            the GPS fix.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Proposed: camera-based pathfinding</h4>
          <p class="text-white/40">
            Next sensor to add (if time and budget allow) is a Pi Camera Module on the CSI port
            for forward-looking obstacle detection via
            <span class="text-white/50">OpenCV</span>. The LiDAR gives range-based avoidance but
            can't tell you what the obstacle is. A camera feed with basic classification would
            let the vessel distinguish debris from a kayak from a wave crest.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">In progress: custom carrier PCB</h4>
          <p class="text-white/40">
            I'm designing a <span class="text-white/50">KiCad</span> carrier PCB that mounts
            under the Pi Zero 2 W as a HAT-style board. It consolidates power regulation (5 V
            and 3.3 V rails from a single LiPo input),
            <span class="text-white/50">I2C sensor headers</span> for the MLX90640, GPS, and IMU,
            servo PWM output, UART crossover to the Uno, CSI passthrough for the camera, and
            status LEDs. Basically replacing the rats-nest of breadboard jumper wires with
            a single board.
          </p>
        </div>
        <PhotoGallery
          client:only="react"
          images={[
            { src: "/projects/oerc/boat-thumb.png", alt: "Autonomous model vessel — side view", caption: "Side profile of the completed autonomous model vessel on its display stand" },
            { src: "/projects/oerc/topfrontviewboat.jpg", alt: "Top-down view of vessel internals", caption: "Top-down view showing sensor mounts, wiring, and electronics layout" },
            { src: "/projects/oerc/comp-1.jpg", alt: "AEGIS project poster and vessel display", caption: "AEGIS: Autonomous Environmental Guardian for Intelligent Search and Rescue — competition poster with vessel" },
            { src: "/projects/oerc/comp-2.jpg", alt: "Team photo at competition", caption: "Team presenting the autonomous vessel at the engineering competition" },
            { src: "/projects/oerc/boatwork1.jpg", alt: "Workshop — prototyping and testing", caption: "Workshop session — prototyping and testing components" },
            { video: "/projects/oerc/boat-vid-1.mp4", alt: "Vessel testing video 1", caption: "Testing the autonomous vessel" },
            { video: "/projects/oerc/boat-vid-2.mp4", alt: "Vessel testing video 2", caption: "Tank testing — wall tracking and obstacle avoidance" },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <!-- MAPS Desktop Client -->
      <div class="glass-card p-6">
        <h3 class="font-display font-600 text-white/85 mb-1">MAPS Desktop Client — NURBS Surface Viewer & Seakeeping Suite</h3>
        <p class="text-xs font-mono text-white/25 mb-3">C++ · Qt · OpenGL · GLSL · NURBS · IGES · Hydrodynamics</p>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            <span class="text-white/70">MAPS</span> (Motion Analysis Program Suite) is a
            frequency-domain <span class="text-white/70">potential flow solver</span> for
            wave-body interaction, developed by Drs Wei Qiu and Heather Peng. Its core method is
            the <span class="text-white/70">panel-free method (PFM)</span>, which skips the flat-panel
            approximation used in conventional BEM solvers and instead evaluates boundary integrals
            directly on the exact NURBS geometry via Gaussian quadrature, with the Rankine singularity
            removed analytically through <span class="text-white/70">desingularization</span>.
            The solver had no GUI. You'd hand-edit plaintext .in config files, run the binary from a
            terminal, then parse output files separately. I built a desktop client in
            <span class="text-white/70">C++</span> and <span class="text-white/70">Qt 6</span>
            that wraps the full pipeline: geometry import and inspection, solver configuration
            and execution, and post-processing with interactive charts, all in one window.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Geometry & visualization</h4>
          <p>
            The viewer parses <span class="text-white/70">IGES files</span> (Entity 128) and
            evaluates <span class="text-white/70">NURBS surfaces</span> using
            <span class="text-white/70">Cox-de Boor recursion</span> for B-spline basis functions,
            with adaptive grid density based on control point count. Rendering is two-pass: the
            first pass tessellates each patch into a triangle mesh, uploads it to VBOs/IBOs, and
            draws it with a <span class="text-white/70">Phong fragment shader</span> in GLSL.
            The second pass overlays Gaussian points and normal arrows via QPainter projected
            through the cached MVP matrix. Each hull body sits in a shared world-space coordinate
            system with its own position, heading, and color palette, so you can load multi-body
            configs (catamarans, trimaran floats, barges alongside a vessel) and see them together.
            Surface normals are editable per-patch with full undo and IGES rewrite, since the
            solver is sensitive to normal orientation and a single flipped patch will blow up the
            solution. The app also overlays MAPS .geom output (<span class="text-white/70">Gaussian quadrature coordinates</span>,
            <span class="text-white/70">unit normals</span>, and <span class="text-white/70">surface Jacobians</span>) directly on the mesh so you can verify
            discretization quality before running a full solve.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Analysis workflow</h4>
          <p>
            All MAPS input parameters are exposed through form dialogs: principal dimensions,
            mass and inertia matrices, wave heading and frequency ranges, per-patch Gauss point
            counts, and 25+ solver control flags (m-term treatment, forward-speed Green function
            selection, catamaran mode, etc.). The app assembles the complete .in namelist file
            and launches the solver as a child process with stdout piped to a console widget in
            real time. It handles zero-speed and forward-speed formulations,
            <span class="text-white/70">irregular frequency removal</span> via waterplane lid
            points, <span class="text-white/70">mean drift forces</span> (near-field and far-field),
            catamaran/trimaran <span class="text-white/70">rigid-body coupling</span>, and random
            sea spectral statistics
            (<span class="text-white/70">Pierson-Moskowitz</span>, <span class="text-white/70">JONSWAP</span>).
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Results viewer</h4>
          <p>
            Tabbed panels for <span class="text-white/70">motion RAOs</span>, added mass,
            <span class="text-white/70">damping coefficients</span>, wave exciting forces,
            diffraction forces, drift forces, and section loads, each with amplitude/phase toggle
            and split-by-DOF or combined chart views. Drag-to-zoom, hover tooltips with exact
            values, scientific notation on axes. You can load multiple output files and compare
            them side by side with stable per-dataset color assignment across 10 high-contrast
            colors. Added mass is displayed in tonnes with a full
            <span class="text-white/70">6×6 coupling matrix</span> view or diagonal-only,
            depending on whether you care about cross-coupling terms.
          </p>

          <div class="rounded-lg border border-dashed border-white/10 p-8 text-center text-sm text-white/25 font-mono">
            Screenshots coming soon
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- MASS report -->
      <div id="mass-report" class="glass-card p-6">
        <h3 class="font-display font-600 text-white/85 mb-2">MASS connectivity research</h3>
        <p class="text-xs font-mono text-white/25 mb-3">MASS · IMO · GMDSS · S-100 · FMEA · STPA · Maritime PKI · SD-WAN</p>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            Research paper produced at JVPLabs / OERC under Dr. Wei Qiu as part of the
            <span class="text-white/70">CISMaRT</span> research group. The central question:
            are current connectivity architectures and governance mechanisms actually sufficient
            for <span class="text-white/70">Maritime Autonomous Surface Ships</span>, or do MASS
            and <span class="text-white/70">S-100 data ecosystems</span> need oversight models
            comparable to <span class="text-white/70">GMDSS</span>, Cospas-Sarsat, and LRIT?
          </p>
          <p>
            When a vessel operates with reduced or no crew, the communication link stops being a
            convenience and becomes a safety-critical dependency. A degraded or compromised link
            directly affects the ability to monitor vessel state, validate automated decisions, or
            intervene during emergencies. The same applies to S-100 digital maritime data, where
            high-resolution navigational, environmental, and safety products have to be delivered,
            authenticated, and ingested in real time for things like dynamic under-keel clearance.
          </p>
          <p>
            I mapped MASS operational modes and mission threads to phase-specific connectivity
            requirements across pre-departure, transit, constrained-water maneuvering, degraded
            conditions, and recovery, using formal risk methods including
            <span class="text-white/70">FMEA</span>,
            <span class="text-white/70">STPA</span>, and
            <span class="text-white/70">Bayesian network</span> hybrid frameworks to characterize
            mode-transition hazards. I surveyed the full communication technology landscape
            available to MASS (GEO/LEO satellite constellations, HAPS, coastal LTE/5G,
            <span class="text-white/70">VDES</span>), link redundancy via
            <span class="text-white/70">SD-WAN</span> orchestration, and cybersecurity
            infrastructure including <span class="text-white/70">Maritime Connectivity Platform
            PKI</span>, SECOM-authenticated data exchange, Galileo OSNMA, and AIS spoofing
            defenses. I also pulled governance and assurance models from aviation
            (<span class="text-white/70">ICAO RCP framework</span>, UAS C2 link standards,
            DO-178C), automotive (ISO 26262 ASIL, UNECE R155/R156/R157), and public safety
            communications to see what translates.
          </p>
          <p>
            From that I built a proposed <span class="text-white/70">tiered RCP-Maritime
            framework</span> that matches governance intensity to service criticality, from
            real-time safety-of-life control links requiring GMDSS-style centralized oversight
            down to background transfers governed through lighter federated models. The gap
            synthesis identified ten specific governance, technical, and assurance shortfalls
            where current mechanisms fall short, each tagged with downstream implications for
            risk analysis and regulatory adoption.
          </p>
          <p>
            The main findings: there is no mandatory connectivity performance standard for MASS,
            no independent oversight for commercial connectivity providers serving autonomous
            vessels, maritime PKI adoption is entirely voluntary, and there is no standardized
            mechanism for MASS to publish fallback behavior profiles to traffic management
            authorities. IMO proceedings at <span class="text-white/70">MSC 110</span> confirmed
            that connectivity governance will be deferred beyond the non-mandatory MASS Code
            expected for adoption in May 2026, which validated the paper's argument that this is
            one of the most significant unresolved problems in the regulation of maritime autonomy.
            This work directly shaped AEGIS's comms architecture, specifically around what the
            vessel should stream live vs. log locally, and how it degrades when satellite links
            fail.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

</ProjectLayout>